        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/389770563?book_show_action=true">Aug 12, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aura" href="/user/show/9936091-aura">Aura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9936091-aura?shelf=all-time-favorites">all-time-favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9936091-aura?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer389770563" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12162669271102307815">I listened to the audio unabridged version and I cant get this book out of my mind. The epilogue includes an actual interviews with an African American midwife who was taught to &quot;catch babies&quot; by her mother. What a delightful end to a fantastic book. <br/>This story about African American women, healers and midwives is written by a white man in a strong, poignant, heartfelt and truthful voice. Jonathan Odell speaks about the People, Africans slaves, whose stories were stolen by slavery. The healing c</span>
  <span id="freeText12162669271102307815" style="display:none">I listened to the audio unabridged version and I cant get this book out of my mind. The epilogue includes an actual interviews with an African American midwife who was taught to "catch babies" by her mother. What a delightful end to a fantastic book. <br />This story about African American women, healers and midwives is written by a white man in a strong, poignant, heartfelt and truthful voice. Jonathan Odell speaks about the People, Africans slaves, whose stories were stolen by slavery. The healing comes from remembering the stories about the People and where one comes from. <br />Polly Shine is an unforgettable character. She is not just a healer of the body but more importantly a spiritual healer. She tells Granada "you got to know where you come from to know where you stand. When you know where you stand, you can help the People" (I paraphrase because I listened to the book). This is what this book is about.<br />The previous reviews cover the wonderfulness of this book. All I can add is that this is one of those books that I will be remembered for a long time because of its wisdom and humanity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12162669271102307815" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


